text: FRANCE LA NOUVELLE CARTE D'IDENTITE Plus petite, inviolable et infalsifiable, la nouvelle K carte d'identité numérique> a été présentée le16 mars 2021. Lancée d'abord dans l'Oise puis dans quelques départements, elle est proposée dans toute la France à partir du 2 août 2021. CEV (cachet électronique visible) Signature électronique sécurisée permettant d'authentifier le document. Puce électronique Validité 10 ans. Image changeante avec date de fin de validité surimprimée. contenant les données biométriques du titulaire (photo, empreintes digitales...) + les données de la carte* 1,68m TARLETHOgN 12.022020 PATEDEDELVHNCE/De dae ADRESSEL Address 44 rue DESIRE SAINT CLEMENT RESIDENCE DU PLEIN AIR BAT4 33000 BORDEAUX FRANCE RÉPUBLIQUE FRANÇAISE CARTE NATIONALE D'IDENTITE VIDENTITY CARD NOM/Sumane MARTIN Malys-Gaelle, /Gien names Marie FKA LEUOE/AISSANCE/ANN PARS ofbeth NOWUSAGE) Alenaten name NOM D'USAGE N'DUDOCUMENT fOocumentNs X4RTBPFW4 1102.2030 Siguatate REPUBLIQUE FRANÇAISE FRAX4RTBPFW46<<<<<<<<<<< 07138F3002119FRA<<<<<<<<<<<6 RTINKCMAELYSKGAELLESMARIE<<< Un in - SEXE/S NATIONALITE Nafienalty CATEDENASS.OMPIR 13071990 DATEDEXPIR Expiry dale 384213 2 C adresses peuvent être indiquées. 8,5 cm Fond sécurisé se poursuivant sur les bords transparents. Dispositif holographique afin de protéger la photo. Même format qu'une carte bancaire. Eta aussi À terme, elle permettra de réaliser des démarches administratives en sans avoir besoin de se rendre en mairie ou dans un commissariat par exemple. ligne *nom, prénoms, date et lieu de naissance, sexe, taille, nationalité, adresse, date de délivrance de la carte, date de fin de validité, numéro de la carte, photographie numérisée; empreintes digitales numérisées de deux Source: : ministère VISACTU de l'Intérieur, médias. V doigts.

description: JUSTIFICATIF DE DOMICILE - VOLMUNSTER
text: Liberte Egalité RÉPUBLIQUE MINISTERE DE L'INTERIEUR 2D-DOC un nouvel outil pour sécuriser VOS justificatifs de domicile 2D-DOC Le ministère de l'Intérieur a développé un nouveau type de code- barres, appelés K 2D-DOC> et apposés sur des justificatifs de domicile. Le nom, le prenom et l'adresse sont alors cryptés dans ce code-barres. Avec le soutien financier de P'Union européenne, les agents de préfecture ont été équipés pour déchiffrer ces 2D-DOC et ainsi vérifier la cohérence de ce qui est écrit sur le justificatif de domicile en toutes lettres et en code-barres. EDF et Bouygues-Telecom, en attendant d'autres opérateurs, apposent désormais des 2D-DOC sur leurs factures électroniques ou sur les attestations de contrat téléchargeables depuis le compte-client. Ainsi, leurs clients disposent de justificatifs de domicile sécurisés, que les services des préfectures et des mairies ont désormais l'obligation d'accepter dans le cadre de VOS demandes : de cartes nationales d'identité de passeports de titres de séjour. description: Infos Françaises on Twitter: "ALERTE - La nouvelle #attestation de sortie  en journée est finalement supprimée. Un simple justificatif de domicile  (document d'identité) est désormais nécessaire pour tout déplacement dans  un rayon
text: PREMIER MINISTRE Liberté Egalité Fraternité Service Communucation Hôtel de Matignon, le 20 mars 2021 COMMUNIQUE DE PRESSE Les règles relatives aux attestations de déplacement applicables à compter de ce samedi 20 mars sont simplifiées et allégées: 1.Leur présentation sera simplifiée e:les attestations mises en ligne sur le site du ministère de I'Intérieur distingueront dorénavant deux situations distinctes: l'attestation applicable le soir et la nuit (entre 19h le soir et 6h du matin) sur tout le territoire national, au titre du couvre-feu; l'attestation applicable en journée (entre 6h du matin et 19h le soir) dans les seuls 16 départements soumis à des mesures renforcées. 2. Pour ces 16 departements en journée, l'obligation de se munir d'une attestation en cas de sortie sera supprimée dans certaines situations : à compter de ce jour, pour tout déplacement dans un rayon de 10 kilomètres autour de son domicile entre 6h et 19h, il ne sera plus obligatoire de produire une attestation et donc de justifier du motif de son déplacement. En cas de contrôle, il sera demandé de produire un simple justificatif de domicile (ex: : document d'identité). L'attestation etla justification du motif du déplacement continueront d'être requises pour les déplacements de plus de 10 kilomètres (soit au sein du departement, soit pour des déplacements inter-regionaux). Deux nouveaux modèles d'attestation seront mis en ligne sur le site du ministère de l'Intérieur dans les prochaines heures.

text: PREMIER MINISTRE Liberté Egalité Fraternité Service Communication Hôtel de Matignon, le 20 mars 202 COMMUNIQUE DE PRESSE Les règles relatives aux attestations de déplacement applicables à compter de ce samedi 20 mars sont simplifiées et allégées: : 1. Leur présentation sera simplifiée : les attestations mises en ligne sur le site du ministère de I'Intérieur distingueront dorénavant deux situations distinctes : - l'attestation applicable le soir et la nuit (entre 19h le soir et 6h du matin) sur tout le l'attestation applicable en journée (entre 6h du matin et 19h le soir) dans les seuls 16 territoire national, au titre du couvre-feu; départements soumis à des mesures renforcées. 2. Pour ces 16 départements en journée, l'obligation de se munir d'une attestation en cas de sortie sera supprimée dans certaines situations : à compter de ce jour, pour tout déplacement dans un rayon de 10 kilometres autour de son domicile entre 6h et 19h, il ne sera plus obligatoire de produire une attestation et donc de justifier du motif de son déplacement. En cas de contrôle, il sera demandé de produire un simple justificatif de domicile (ex : document d'identité). L'attestation et la justification du motif du déplacement continueront d'être requises pour les déplacements de plus de 10 kilomètres (soit au sein du département, soit pour des déplacements inter-régionaux). description: Lire sa fiche de paie - SUD Éducation 93
text: - Sudos Déchiffrer sa fiche de paie Comprendre sa fiche de paie dans 'Education Nationale est un véritable casse-tête : entre les heures sup' et les primes payées des mois en retard, les codes obscures, il est difficile de vérifier ce qu'on touche, sans oublier que les fiches de paie sont bien souvent distribuées avec plusieurs mois de retard ! Le bandeau d'information rassemble toutes les informations permettant de calculer des paies pour La fiche de paie est composée de trois grands ensembles : 1-Le bandeau d'informations Le calendrier 'année 2018 Lundi 29/01 Lundi 26/02 Mercredi 28/03 Jeudi 26/04 Lundi 29/05 Mercredi 27/06 Mercredi 29/08 Mercredi 26/09 Lundi 29/10 Mercredi 28/11 Temps partiel la rémunération de l'agent-e. Plusieurs informations du bandeau sont donc à ventier - (CN le corps (professeur certifié, PE, professeur agrégé, AED...) et le grade le nombre d'enfants à charge I ouvre droit au SFT (Supplement l'échelon : les échelons passés de septembre à décembre Classe Normale, HC Hors Classe...) Familial de Traintement), s'applique aux entants jusqu'à l'age de 20 ans. n'apparaissent souvent qu'en janvier. Vous pouvez consulter votre échelon ainsi que la date de passage à l'échelon supérieur sur i-prof. calculer votre salaire. L'indice dépend du corps, du grade et de r'échelon. + la NBI (Nouvelle Bonification Indiciaire) permet de prendre en compte le Temps Partiel : correspond à la quotité de salaire versé. l'indice ou nombre d'heures : lindice de rémunération permet de Vendredi 27/07 les points dûs au poste spécifique occupé dans le calcul de l'indice. Ex:. un 80% ou 50%.. Grade PROF. CERTIFLE CN 2-Le détail du salaire Ent, a charge 00 ech. 05 Ind./Nb 1 0466 TX hr/NBI On observe ensuite sur la fiche de paie un tableau à cinq colonnes - Codes et Elements indiquent tous les éléments à déduire ou a ajouter au traitement brut - à payer I le crédit de l'agent-e, tout ce que lui doit lemployeur, c'est-a-dire le traintement, les + à déduire : les cotisations sociales à la charge de l'agent-e, elles sont retirées du salaire brut: : pension civile (retenue PC) = la retraite, CSG, CRDS (Contribution à la Réduction de la Dette Sociale), Contribution Solidarité (= l'Assurance Chomage), RAFP (= caisse complementaire de retraite). pour information : les cotisations patronales versées par l'Etat pour l'agent-e ( maladie, pour calculer le salaire net. primes et les indemnités. allocations familiales, retraites...). 3-Le pied de la fiche de paie Ne restez pas isolé-e, syndiquez-vous ! 9-11 rue Génin, 93200 Saint-Denis 01.55.84.41.26 ou 06.88.66.47.23 contact@sudeducatien.erg MR/mmastreascalemsieng La partie intérieur du bulletin de paie comporte les informations défendez vos droits, concemant lagent-e (son numéro de compte, son numéro de sécurité sociale), la date du virement et les informations détaillées dans le tableau montant pris en compte dans le calcul des cotisations. l'année du 1er. janvier au 31 décembre indique le montant qui permettra de calculer l'impot sur le revenu. Le montant imposable du mois est égal au traitement net augmenté de la CSG non déductible, de la CRDS et de la à 5 colonnes. La Base SS (Base Sécurité Sociale) du mois indique le Pour contacter Sud Educ' 93 Le montant imposable du mois et le montant imposable de cotisation pour la mutuelle, votre salaire. le montant net à payer indique la somme qui vous sera versée,

Genetic Epidemiology 5:265-275 (1988) Estimating Genetic Parameters of Survival Distributions: A Multifactorial Model Joanne M. Meyer and Lindon J. Eaves Department of Human Genetics, Medical College of Virginia, Richmond For a number of genetically influenced Unesses, age of onset is correlated between relatives. In some cases, age of onset also serves as an index of an individual's inherited liability to an ilness. Typically, survival models for age of onset distri- butions do not allow for these effects. We have used the gamma distribution as the basis of a model which specifies genetic variability in age of onset. Specifically, we allow the hazard frequency parameter of the gamma distribution to be a under various gamma models indicate that age of onset correlations may be strikingly different from correlations in liability. Maximum hikelthood estimation procedures were used 10 obtain parameter estimates from simulated data sets and to determine whether it is possible to discriminate between gamma processes of different order. The results for 1,000 pairs of twins (500 monozygotic and 500 dizygotic) gave parameter estimates that were fairly accurate but that decreased in precision as the order of the gamma process increased. We discuss the effect this may have on inferences made about age of onset. Key words: age of onset correlations, survival models, gamma distribution monotonic function of an individual's inherited to an illness. liability pfivijat Simulations INTRODUCTION Genetic analyses of illnesses and behaviors showing a variable age of onset require a knowledge of the cumulative probability of onset by given ages. Some approachés [Weinberg, 1915; Stromgren, 1938; Risch, 1983) derive this probability from prior age of onset distributions. Others (Elston, 1973; Heimbuch et al., 1980; Risch, 1983] estimate parameters of a cumulative age of onset distribution from the data. Interoffice Memorandum Tobacco Company NRpaic Subject: Market Share Study Date: November 8, 1991 To: Ms. R. H. Steele From: Tory Payne Objective: To investigate the relationship between mutagenicity and weight of tobacco burned, tar, cigarette length, and air dilution for RJR products. Summary: Mutagenicity estimates using a nonlinear regression model were obtained on a sample of 24 RJR products. Correlations between mutagenicity (estimated from linear and nonlinear regression models) and weight of tobacco burned, tar, cigarette length and air dilution were determined. Preliminary regression analyses were performed to investigate the relationship of the above-mentioned variables to mutagenicity. Conclusions: Tar and air dilution were the best single predictors of mutagenicity on a revertants/mg tar basis. Tar was the best single predictor for mutagenicity on a revertants/cigarette basis, followed by weight of tobacco burned. Various combinations of weight, length, tar and air dilution predicted mutagenicity better than any variable by itself. However, variables other than these influence mutagenicity since the percent of variability explained ranged from only 48% to 82%. € a a a

All rights of any nature, whatsoever, reserved. 18-494X130:0131.00 Applications of Neutron Activation Analysis to the Study of Age-Related Neurological Diseases W. D. EHMANN, 1* W. R. MARKESBERY,234 E.J. KASARSKIS,4 D.E. VANCE, S. S. KHARE, J. D. HORD,' AND Departments of 'Chemistry, Neurology, Pathology, and Sanders Brown Research Center on Aging, University of Kentucky, Lexington, C.M. THOMPSON' KY40506. ABSTRACT Although the etiology and pathogenesis of Alzheimer's disease, Pick's disease, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis are still unknown, it has been suggested that perturbations in element metabolism may play a role. Even if not causative factors, these imbalances may prove to be markers that could aid in diagnosis. We have emploved a se- quential neutron activation analysis (NAA) procedure to determine elemental concentrations in brain, hair, fingernails, blood, and cere- brospinal fluid (CSF) of these patients and age-matched controls. Samples are first irradiated with accelerator-produced 14-MeV neu- trons tor determination of nitrogen and phosphorus, then with reac- tor thermal neutrons for the instrumental determination of 16-18 mi- nor and trace elements, and, finaily, reactor-irradiated again, followed by a rapid radiochemical separation procedure (RNAA) to determine four additional elements. Major advantages of NAA are: (1) its simultaneous multielement capability; (2) the relative treedom trom reagent and laboratory contamination; (3) the absence of major matrix effects; and (4) an adequate sensitivity for most elements of in- terest. Ranges of concentrations by INAA and RNAA in selected con- trol tissues and interelement correlations in control brain are pre- sented to illustrate results obtained by the procedure. Longitudinal studies of tissues from Alzheimer's disease (AD) and amyotrophic lat- eral sclerosis (ALS) patients are still in progress. "Author to whom all correspondence and reprint requests should be addressed. Biological Trace Element Rescarch 19 Vol. 13. 1987

Sept. 1, 1995 J.Immunology Identification and Localization of a Developmental Stage- Specific Promoter Activity from the Murine A5 Gene' Jun Yang, Michele A. Glozak, and Bonnie B. Blomberg Department of Microbiology and Immunology, University of Miami School of Medicine, Miami, FL 33101 The A5 protein is expressed in pre-B cells in association with VpreB and u-heavy chains, and is critical for differentiation to the B cell stage. Pre-B cell-specific expression of the. A5 and VpreB genes is regulated at the level of transcription initiation. In this report, we have identified several DNase 1-hypersensitive sites 2.5- to 6.0-kb downstream of the A5 gene, which are present in the pre-B cell line 70Z/3, but not in the myeloma cell line J558L. These sites, however, were shown to have no transcriptional enhancer activity as measured by transient trans- fection. Enhancer activity was identified within a 361-bp fragment (-296 to +65, where +1 is the major 5' transcription initiation site) upstream of the mouse A5 gene. This activity is orientation and position independent, and is also tissue and differentiation stage specific (active in pre-B but not B and T cells). Deletion constructs indicate that three adjacent areas (-210to -169, -153 to -64, and -64 to -22) are all necessary for enhancer activity. Pre-B cell-specific promoter activity was shown to reside within the -219 to +109 fragment. Basal promoter activity resides within the -64 to +109 fragment, but is not tissue specific or stage specitic. A negative element within the -101 to -64 region is active in all lymphoid cell lines tested and therefore cannot by itself be responsible for the tissue and stage specificity. The data indicate that the elements responsible for the enhancer activity. (-210 to -22) are part of the A5 gene promoter and likely confer the tissue and stage specificity via positive elements within the -210 to -22 region. NACS JOINS COALITION AGAINST TOBACCO SALES TO MINORS 82021 At: a December nationai press conference, the National Association of Convenience Stores (NACS) and the nation's largest retailer and wholesaler trade groups launched the most comprehensive effort to date to prevent tobacco sales to minors. The partnering groups, who represent more than 150,000 retailers nationwide, will work together through the Coalition for Responsible Tobacco Retailing (CRTR) with' support from tobacco manulacturers. The primary function of CRTR, a non-profit orga- nization, is to provide training and educa- tional materials to retailers. To carry out this mission, the Coalition has established the Responsible Tobacco Retailer Program : or "We Card" program.  In the next few months, CATR will ship, "We Card" kits to retailers who request them to feature the logo. The kits are troe of charge With more than 25 million tobacco trans- actions a day in the convenience store industry, it is imperative that our store employees have an array of tools that will assist them in preventing tobacco sales to minors," said Fred Higgins, NACS Chairman of the Board and Chaiman and CEO of Minit Mart Foods (Bowling Green, KY). "As a retailer, I can attest to the fact that my store employees are on the front lines in preventing tobacco sales to youth. Regardless of whether a minor is using an altered ID or an adult is purchasing tobacco for a minor, our commitment is to ensure that these illegal sales are not made. This industry-wide program provides retailers with everything they need to prevent tobac- cO sales to minors including specific state laws and guidelines wherever a store owner For more information on the program or to request the free store signage and training materials, call NACS fax 1-800-555-4833 * and key in document #226. lanian Id... for all retailers. operates." (212) 880-4146 PHILIP MORRIS TO INTRODUCE NEW SUPER ULTRA LOW TARNICOTINE CIGARETTE MERIT SETS NEW STANDARD IN SUPER ULTRALIGHT SMOKING New "Lowest" Tar/Nicotine MERIT ULTIMA To Be Launched Nationally NEW YORK, January 7, 1992 - Merit Ultima, a new Super Ultra Light addition to the Merit brand family, will be launched nationally on February 18 by Philip Morris U.S.A. The new brand will offer superior taste and smokeability" at the lowest levels of tar and nicotine. New Merit Ultima sets a new standard for the lowest" segment of - the premium market. It offers a flavor alternative to Carlton and Now smokers as well as to smokers who are interested in switching to a cigarette at the super ultra light level. By using Merit's patented enriched flavor technology and a new dual concentric filter, Merit Ultima offers the great taste heritage of its parent brand and a smooth, easy draw. And, Merit Ultima is the first cork-tipped entry in the category. Merit Ultima kings contain 1 mg. tar and 0.1 mg. of nicotine; and 100's contain 2 mg. tar and 0.2 mg. of nicotine. I (more)

Todd, Esq. Tobacco Research Council Glen House, Stag Place London, S.W.1 England Dear Mr. Todd: In recent talks with Dr. Carl G. Baker, Director of the National Cancer Institute, the desirability of forming an international stucy group concerned with research into tobacco and health problems was discussed. This letter is to invite you on behalf of your organization to participate in this The proceedings will aim at providing the relatively few active investigators in tobacco. and health research programs with an opportunity to discuss freely current and future research prograns with the intent of reaching connon objectives more quickly. The group will be composed of investigators primarily involved in tobacco and health research oriented towards producing less harmful smoking products. The partici- pants must be both willing and able to share with other investigators what is being learned from their current activities and openly discuss plans for future research in the field. It is thought that by bringing such a group of experts together to review ongoing studies and to plan future investigations jointly less harmful tobacco products will be available sooner and costly research projects will not be duplicated unneces- sarily. The meetings would be held at yearly intervals with the different organizations acting as host. information and study group.

Small Business . -1 Committee ETAL Karen Kerrigan President Small Business Survival Committee Karen Kerrigan is president of the 40,000 member Small Business Survival Committee (SBSC), a nationwide nonprofit, nonpartisan small business advocacy organization representing America's small business and entrepreneunal sector. SBSC works to promote policies and retorms which foster economic growth and entrepreneurship. Ms. Kerrigan is a nationally recognized spokesperson on a wide range of public policy issues, who has testified numerous times on behalf of small business interests before the U.S. Congress. She has appeared on such television programs as CNBC'S America's Talking Network, C-SPAN, The Wall Street. Journal Report, European Business News, The Home Business Show, NET's Capitol Watch and writes a twice-monthly syndicated column for the American City Business Journals, an influential network of more than sixty local business journals nationwide. Ms. Kerrigan also serves as president of the Small Business Survival Foundation, a research and education organization that studies the impact of government policy on entrepreneurship and economic growth. She is also a principal in Capitol Hill Research, a political and economic research service. SBSC, which was recognized by Your Company magazine as one of the most powerful small business lobbying groups in Washington, D.C., has been cited by Investor's Business Daily, The Wall Street. Journal, The Washington Times, The Washington Post, The New York Times, National Journal, Business Week, Entrepreneur, Fortune Magazine, Bloomberg Business News, The Boston Herald, The Philadelphia Inquirer, The Rush Limbaugh Show, The Michael Regan Show and hundreds oflocal newspapers. a 1320 18th Street, N.W., Suite 200 - Washington, D.C. 20036 Tel: (202)785-0238 - Fax (202)822-8118 www.sbsc.org

PUBLIC RELATIONS COUNSEL andAssociates,/nc P.O. BOX 523 * 13 LINCOLN ROAD GREATI NECK, NIY: 11021 (212) 895-7445 FOR: THE COUNCIL FOR TOBACCO RESEARCH-U.S.A., INC. FOR RELEASE IN AM'S OF TUESDAY, JAN. 26, 1971 Lgant INEUVS RAMM ASSUMES LEADERSHIP OF COUNCIL FOR TOBACCO RESEARCH New York - H.H. Ramm, a long-time tobacco industry executive, has been elected chairman and president of The Council for Tobacco Research-U.S.A., Inc. He had been act- ing chairman for the last two years. Recently he retired from R.J. Reynolds Industries, Inc., Winston-Salem, N.C. Ramm, a native of Chicago, received his undergraduate education at the University of Minnesota and was graduated from Harvard Law School in 1929. He practiced law in New York City until 1946 and then joined the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Company in Winston-Salem as solicitor and assist- ant to the chairman of the board. He was elected a direc- tor of the company in 1946, became general counsel in 1955, and a vice president in 1970. In 1970, when R.J. Reynolds Industries was formed, he became chairman of the executive committee, senior vice president, general counsel, and a director. He held these positions until his retirement on December 31, 1970. The Council for Tobacco Research had its origin in 1954 when representatives of tobacco manufacturers, growers and warehousemen organized the Tobacco Industry Research Com- mittee to support research by independent scientists into all aspects of tobacco use and health. The research pro- gram is the responsibility of a Scientific Advisory Board, currently consisting of 10 noted physicians and scientists, which has so far awarded grants to 251 scientists for a total 2a 2 - of more than $17,000, 000. -0-

Comments on EPA document EPA/600/6-90/006B; Respiratory Health Effects of Passive Smoking: Lung Cancer and Other Disorders (dated May 1992). JUL 161992 R. A. PAGES Introduction I have read the draft of this report, and in general I' am impressed with the thoroughness with which the authors have addressed the issues raised. Unfortunately, lack of time does not permit me to respona to all of it, but there are some sections of the report where I have put my comments in writing. These comments cover inconsistencies in the report, some possible methodological errors, and a number of My specific comments follow, divided into two sections (the more substative points coming first). Within each section, the order in which the points are presented follows their position in the report, and does not reflect their importance. In a number of cases, attention to the issues raised would, in my view, improve the quality of the final report. I would particularly draw attention to points 1.9, 1.10 and 1.1. typographical errors. Substantive points 1.1 (page 5-9, lines 13-12 from bottom). Figure 5-1 is said to show (v]alues of the test statistics (the standardized log odds ratio ..) : plotted'. In fact this figure does no such thing; it appears instead to be a plot of the p-values associated with these test statistics. The actual values of the log odds ratios are not indicated in the figure. To show both the log ORS chemselves and their associated P-values would need a two-dimensional plot; the associated normal distribution could still be shown along the appropriate 1.2 (page 5-9, second paragraph, and Table 5-8). It is not clear to me why the relative weights have been made to sum to 100 within countries. For countries with only one study (eg Scotland) this means the entry in Table 5-8 is non- informative. Presentation of the absolute weight would be 1.3 (page 5-10, lines 1-5). The first sentence here is rather unclear at first. I assume that what is meant is that for any value of x (where x is the list of p-values given in the report: 0.5, 0.4 etc.) the observed number of studies with a P-value less than x is significantly larger than the number of studies involved). I think it would be better to use the word 'studies' than 'outcomes', and to say 'as large here are not independent, and although no claim is made that they are, neither is any warning given that they are not. Finally, I am not convinced by the statement that '(the) conclusion is not attributable to a few extreme outcomes that might be aberrant in some way'. If there were enough of such margin. figures. It's called reinsu- rance and the merry-so-round takes in New York, London and Zurich. The qpestion is where the buck will stop al the end of the reinsurance line. S one senior Lloyd's underwriter pur it: "Irs like a game of pass the parcel. And to be honest, we don't know exactly who's going to be holding it when, the music stops." There is even confusion over how many insurance) companies are being sued.! The ligure varies between, 271 and 33. And Manville's legal action is just the reason why Britain's insurance market is now searching its books and checking policies written 40. yeurs ago. Claims for compensation over asbestose-related heatth problems have been such that the insurance cover American companies have been able to get in the United States is, now almost exhausted. So claims are beginning to everflow into the United Kingdom. particularly into Lloyd' s of London.. And the music is likely to go on for some time. particu- larly as the American courts are currently giving jud. gments diametrically opposed 10 one another. - A $ a  NPUuus

CORESTA 1982 SYMPOSIUM ABSTRACT FORM AUTHOR(S) (indicate presenting author): J. G. Nepomuceno (presenting), A. G. Kallianos, J. E. Wickham, and A. E. Stagg Philip Morris Research Center, P. 0. Box 26583, Richmond, Virginia, 23261 TITLE OF PAPER: REFINEMENTS TO THE FTC PROCEDURE FOR THE QUANTITATIVE AFFILIATION AND ADDRESS: DETERMINATION OF TPM IN CIGARETTE SMOKE STUDY GROUP: ABSTRACT TEXT: A lightweight and disposable filter holder assembly used in the collection of - total particulate matter in cigarette smoke was developed as a replacement for the currently used Lucite filter holder. Not only are these new holders lighter in weight (5 grams versus 27 grams for the Lucite holder) but the inconvenient and time-consuming steps of washing these holders in an alcohol bath and drying prior to subsequent use are also eliminated. During the development of these holders, it was noted that certain types of materials, including Lucite, were very sensitive to changes in the moisture content of the environment resulting in highly variable TPM resuits. These variations become most significant for extremely low yield cigarettes where negative TPM deliveries have been frequently encountered during the analysis. A negative TPM result indicates a loss of weight of the filter assembly the smoking procedure. These negative numbers have been obtained even when during the filter pads were clearly stained by the smoke particulate phase indicating that something was collected during the smoking process. Therefore, the apparently negative TPM deliveries must be a result of an artifact in the smoke particulate matter collection procedure. Experimental data are presented showing that the observed artifact is primarily due to some phenomenon occurring at - the surface of the filter holder during, but extraneous to, the particulate matter collection process. This phenomenon is shown to be attributable to the inherent property of certain materials, including Lucite, to easily adsorb In order to minimize the observed bias in the TPM results and thus allow for the collection of more meaningful data, a lightweight and disposable holder made out of polypropylene and polystyrene was developed. In addition to the obvious advantages of being lightweight and disposable, experimental evidence was presented showing that a negative bias which becomes significant at low TPM delivery levels is eliminated through the use of these holders because of their inherent insensitivity to moisture fluctuations in the environment. and desorb moisture from the environment. e 1 € .-Uv 19

Newsday (New York, NY) May 1, 1998, Friday, ALL EDITIONS VIEWPOINTS; Page A57 BIG TOBACCO CANT CUT TEEN SMOKING By. Alan Brody. Alan Brody, a marketing journalist, is the author of - Cigarette Seduction." THE TOBACCO industry may be guilty of many big lies, but Congress and the public health community may be developing a big lie of their own: that the cigaretie companies can undo the phenomenon of teenaged smoking. As Stanton Glantz, author of "Cigarette Papers," wrote: "The tobacco companies know how to get kids smoking and, But the issue is bigger than tobacco companies. Because the settlement talks with the government are based on the tobacco companies" supposed omnipotence, the likely failure will create a whole new layer of corruption all the way from illegal sales to fly-by-night tobacco companies to the potential for more damaging products to enter the gap. Adults tend to have a poor memory of their own youth and why they themselves became smokers. It wasn't because the tobacco companies marketed to them. It was because they marketed to adults and, as teenagers, they desperately A lively grandmother in her 80s confided to me that she started smoking at 10 and quit at 40. That means she began smoking in the 1930s when cigarette ads were still focusing on tobacco leaf quality and Turkish flavor. There were no ads for Leenagers and certainly none for pre-teens. In fact, the country barcly paid. any attention to teens. Conventional wisdom has it that advertising and marketing are responsible for selling tobacco. It helps. But does it cause smoking? The absence of advertising in Finland and, for a while, in Italy showed that cigarettes sell just fine The etiology of smoking runs deeper into the. realm of mystery than legislators and public health oflicials may care to venture. But that is truly where the allure has its origins. Teenagers aren't responding to ads nearly so much as they are Since we as a society have taken no steps to fill a gap in coming-of-age rituals common in other cultures, guess what industry has come to occupy this role? Kids seck a magic path to the "real heart" of adulthood. They will accept danger but they want belonging and a kind of personal guide, the mystical amulet popular in myth. Cigarettes offer this. That When teenagers were invited to tell Congress why they smoke, one girl said she was: a nonsmoker until she watched a talk show where experts cited depression as a reasons teenagers smoked. "So that's what you do!" said the girl, who Thave no objection to taxing the tobacco companies or throwing a few perjurers in the hoosegow. But the demand for smoking is a phenomenon that is not covered by the proposed legislation and both the tobacco companies and the public health groups are going to be left with an embarrassing and costly predicament. As the European experience has shown, raising prices works - for: a while and then kids have a way of: readjusting. A greater fear, as one teenager put: it in an interview with an American Cancer Society worker I spoke with: "if you make them so expensive, we'll just go on to In this politicized environment, iti is easy to believe that legislation can make magic. Or that the tobacco companies are solely responsible for the rise in smoking. When the Centers for Disease Control announced that smoking had increased 30 percent in six years, they were quite pleased because the implication is that the tobacco companies are to blame. But this was also during the most hostile media period tobacco has ever faced. Newspapers, TV networks and even: magazines that once quivered at the thought of losing cigarette ad dollars now thumb their noses, knowing drug given proper economic motivation, they will know how to stop kids from smoking." wanted to be adults. without ads. responding to their own demands of adjusting to the tribulations of growing up. they are about life and death only adds to their "spirit power." apparently had been feeling depressed, and she began smoking. other drugs." n 0 N A 5

Future Imperfect Voices of a Generation Fear for the Status Of American Dream Despite Their Success, Many Feel Their Parents Had More Cause for Optimism Yet Outsiders Still Want sense oe arecuor and bope from our leaders." he says - trom U.S. president to corporae executive, universuy dean and head of the local charity drive. These themes have been resonating, explicitly and implicitly, in the presiden- tial campaign. Both President Bush and Gov. Clinton have tried to harness the widespread malaise among voters and offer hope for the future, Mr. Clinton by invoking "change" at every opportunity, and Mr. Bush by promising that his poll- cies are on the brink of yielding significant A close look at several people who have seen their confidence in the future erode suggests why there is such widespread disillusionment with the American dream. But not everyone is grim. Those who have come from the poorest backgrounds or encountered the greatest hardships seem to retain the most hope. Everyone Seems Defeated' When Mark Donnelly came of age in the 1960s, no problem seemed insoluble. In 1962, as a 20-year-old Army private, Mr. Donnelly went to Oxford, Miss., to protect James Meredith, whose enrollment at the University of Mississippi sparked race riots. For a week, Mr. Donnelly stood outside Mr. Meredith's dormitory with a rifle guarding him against attack. One. student spat on him. he recalls. Mr. Donnelly also served in Vietnam. But after his discharge. he marched on Washington to pro test the war and be- came a regional or- ganizer for Vietnam Vets Against the War. While attend- ing Columbia Uni- versity, Mr. Don- nelly blocked police from entering a building after stu- dents had seized it. "We were a gen- eration that had hoped the world could be a better Mark Donnelly place," says Mr. Donnelly, now a 50-year- old vice president at Chemical Bank in New York City. "We naively thought that problems were solvabie." his view is different. Today, lems he sees - the budget deficit, strato- spheric health-care costs, the AIDS epi- demic and deficient schools - seem insu- perable. The assumption that prosperity would cure social ills has hit the wall of reality in the form of intractable urban poverty and a fury that erupted in Los Angeles this spring. The proportion of households with annual incomes under $15,000 was lower in 1990, after adjustment for inflation, than in 1980 or 1970, but it remained stubbornly close to 25%. "I've become very cynical about the ability of our system to bring about change," Donnelly says. "There's a real malaise in America right now. Everyone seems defeated. You no longer belleve anything's going to get done." Though he concedes that his current economic growth. In By CLARE ANSBERRY And THOMAS F. O'BOYLE Staff Reporters of THE WALL STREET JOURNAL For many Americans, the future seems about as secure as a dandelion puff. An entire generation now reaching middle age is questioning whether they or their children can do better than their parents. Job security went out with three- piece suits, and pundits have coined a new term, aumpies - for downwardly mobile professionals. Today, both mother and father work, not to be rich, but to send kids to college. The complicated family seene looks more like an Andy Warhol canvas than a Norman Rockwell portrait. Statistically, Americans, both rich and poor, are improving their lots. Their buying power has doubled since the 1950s, and their standard of living remains the highest in the world. Others outside the U.S. still believe people can improve their lot in America: The current wave of immi- grants is the largest since early this cen- Even so, many Americans despair about the ruture. In part that's because, in relative terms, America's standard of liv- ing isn't as far ahead of everyone else's as it once was; other countries are catching up. Nor is the U.S. rate of growth as rapid as it once was. And even some affluent Americans have discovered, as their par- ents warned, that money doesa't buy hap piness. The same numbers - one in three Americans told researchers at the Na- tional Opinion Research Center they were "very happy" in both 1957 and 1990. No amount of money ensures happiness, con- cludes David G. Myers in his book "The Pursuit of Happiness": rather, happiness Is satisfaction with wnatever one has. Warren Bennis, a business professor at the University of southern California, has another explanation for this widespread and Mahler-like melancholy. Loe Statistics and Computing Ltd, 17 Cedar Road, Sutton, Surrey SM2 SDA, England (Received in reolsed, form 8 March 1994) Abstract- -The extent to which current, ex- and passive smoking are associated with other risk lactors, and the potential for confounding arising from these associations, was studiod using a representative sample of 9003 British adults. The distribution of 33 lifestyle factors generally considered associated with adverse health were compared in current smokers, ex-smokers, never smokers living with a smoker ("passive smokers") and other never smokers. of the 33 risk factors 27 showed a significantly higher prevalence in heavy smokers than in never smokers and only two showed a lower prevalence. For many risk factors, prevalence increased with amount smoked, decreased with time of smoking cessation and was increased in passive smokers. The possible magnitude of bias from confounding by the risk factors is estimated. Iti is concluded that confounding by multipke risk factors may be an important issue in smoking studies where weak associations are observed. This applies particularly to studics investigating the possible association of passive smoking with various health etfocts. RESEARCH GRANT FROM THE SWEDISH TOBACCO COMPANY EFFECIS OF TOBACCO SMOKE COMPONENTS ON BIOLOGICAL FUNCTIONS, SIUDIPD AT PROJECT TINLE: CELLULAR AND SUB-CEMDULAR LEVELS PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR: Erik Arrhenius OTHER GRANTEES: ADDRESS CF PRINCIPAL INVESTIGATOR: Milyotaxikologiska arbetsgruppen Nallenserglaboratariet Lilla Frescati 104 05 STOCKHOLM GRANT: (Number, Date, Amount) 7206 1 1972-06-21 75.000:- 7206a 1972-12-08 75.000:- ( SUMMARY OF OBJECTIVE AND METHODOLOGY: Isolated and defined tobacco smoke components are to be tested with respect to their possible disruptive effects on the functions of cells and cell-organelles, both in purely in vitro systems where the cells and cell-organelles are directly exposed to the substance tested, and in cambined in vivo and in vitro experiments, where functional disruptions are evaluated through camparisons of cells and cell-organelles fram exposed and non-exposed animals. It is also planned to carry out a number of studies using a perfusion technique in which the effect of a substance can be studied in a campletely isolated organ provided with an artificial circulation system. The purpose of these experiments is to obtain, by means of greater knowledge of the basic functional disruptions which can occur in cells and cell-organelles in short-term experiments, background material to help facilitate the evaluation of the disruptive ettects which can occur in camplete individuals exposed for a considerable length of time to the various substances tested and of the cambined effects of several smoke components. The substances to be tested are being selected in collaboration with the chemical research at the Swedish Tobacco Co. (Asst. Professor Curt Enzell). 2 a

From: The Tobacco Institute, 1735 K St., N. W., Washington, D. C. 20006 Contact: William Kloepfer, Jr. (Home) 469-8434 (Office) 296-8434 FOR USE AFTER 10 A.M., April 29, 1969 Statement of Milton B. Rosenblatt, M.D., before the House Committee on Interstate and Foreign commerce, April 29, 1969. Dr. Rosenblatt is visiting physician at the Metropolitan and Coler Hospitals and associate attending physician at the Flower Fifth Avenue Hospital, all in New York. He is a member of the Council on Undergraduate Medical Education of the American College of Chest Physicians. News Summary "The concept that cigarette smoking is the cause of the increase in lung cancer and emphysema is a colossal blunder, " he says. Dr. Rosenblatt points out lung cancer was well known a century before widespread cigarette smoking. "The only thing new is our ability to diagnose it before autopsy, " he says, pointing to only a three percent diagnostic success before autopsy in a German study of 178 cases between 1887 and 1900, and an 81 percent success in a U. S. Study of 363 cases in 1949-1958. "The increase in lung cancer is therefore a direct result of diagnostic progress, " he reports. "It has been estimated that a diagnostic error of five percent in males and one percent in females among deaths attributed to pneumonia and other resplratory diseases would have resulted in the same incidence of lung cancer in 1914 as in 1950." X-ray, bronchoscopy, surgery and sputum studies have Dr. Rosenblatt points to the declining rate of increase in lung cancer as being "far more compatible with diagnostic progress than 2 with a true increase." He says that "despite all the claptrap concerning the carcinogenic effects of tar and nicotine there is no valid experimental evidence that tobacco extract or smoke all helped make the difference, he says. 2 - C condensates can produce cancer of the lung." ###

Aetanitonal Prees Releace June 25, 1992 PHILIP MORRIS STATEMENT CIPOLLONE DECISION REGARDING UNITED STATES SUPREME COURT Yesterday, the United States Supreme Court rendered the long awaited decision on the Cipollone case. In spite of the anti-tobacco interests' efforts to make the decision seem like a defeat for our industry, the fact is that the Court's verdict was a victory for us. There were three basic issues in this case. The first and most important - referred to as the issue of "failure to warn" - revolved around the question of whether cigarette advertising and label warnings, in effect since the 1960s, provided consumers with an adequate warning of the risk factors associated with smoking and health. On this most important issue, the Court ruled in our favor, and exempted tobacco companies from post-1969 legal claims that consumers were not adequately warned. A second important issue was whether plaintiffs can assert claims that normal, mainstream cigarette advertising and promotion somehow undermined the effectiveness of the health warnings. On this issue, the Court also ruled that post-1969 claims are preempted. The third issue - referred to as intentional misrepresentation - related to the question of whether tobacco companies engaged in knowing deception by concealing from consumers information : c N o  not generally known about the risks of smoking.

Only 11.41 of female doctors smoked compared to 411 of all Norvegian wonen. There seeas to be a widening gap between the doctors and the lay population, because the differences are more marked in the younger age groups, and because nore doctors than lay persons vant to quit smoking. In comparison both to 1952 and to 1974 there was in 1984 a turther considerable decrease in the proportion of doctors who smoke, both within and across age cohorts. (not the sane persons), with the exception of persons 65 years of age and older. The decrease in smoking among males is nuch stceper among doctors than in the Norvagian male population. Smoking proportions are increasing in the female population, and reducing sharply among female physicians. (Fig. 1) 251 of male and 151 of female doctors are now ex-smokers, from this it nay be inferred that 2.400 Horwegian doctors have quit seoking. The doctors who continue smoking have not cut down on their tobacco use. The nean consumption per smoker was 14 cigarettes per day for male doctors and 12 cigarettes per day for female doctors. This difference is almost identical to the doctors' con- sumption in 1974 and to the consumption of the general population in 1984. Vhen asked to predict their snoking habits in 5 years, only 111 of male doctors and 41 of female doctors whosmoke were certain that they would smoke in 1989, whereas 401 of the nen and 541 of the wonen think it likely or certain that they vill quit smoking. If their own predictions were truc, the overall rates of smoking in 1989 vould be 111 for male doctors and 51 for female doctors. PHILIP MORRIS Inc New York, New York CONTACT: Dolly Colby 212-878-2144 COURT RULES KEY FLORIDA MEDICAID AGENCY IS UNCONSTITUTIONAL; SEVERELY NARROWS APPLICATION OF CONTROVERSIAL LAW TALLAHASSEE, Fla., June 28 - A circuit judge in Tallahassee today declared key provisions of the controversial 1994 Amendments to the Medicaid Third-Party Liability Act unconstitutional and held that the state agency charged with administering the state's Medicaid program is unconstitutionally structured. Charles R. Wall, senior vice president and deputy general counsel for Philip Morris, said the ruling should provide the basis for the dismissal of a claim by the State of Florida. Today's ruling came in a declaratory judgment case filed by the Associated Industries of Florida, Philip Morris Inc. and others. "Because the court ruled that the state agency is unconstitutionally structured, we believe that the claim based on the state's Third-Party Medicaid Liability Act should now be dismissed," said Wall. That case is pending in circuit court in West Palm Beach. In addition, today's ruling clarified a crucial issue the State of Florida sought to obscure last week in media interviews after the hearing leading to today's ruling. The Court held that the new Medicald law applies only to allegedly tortious conduct occurring AFTER July 1, 1994, the date the new law In his ruling, Circuit Judge F.E. Steinmeyer said the law "may only be applied prospectively - specifically, to conduct of potential third-party defendants that occurred after the amendments' effective date of July 1, 1994. No party shall be held liable under the amendments for conduct or activities that "This could well be the beginning of the end of this lawsuit by the State of Florida," Wall said. "The State's claims governed by the new Medicaid law are essentially based on allegediy tortious acts occurring before the effective date of this law and therefore cannot be the basis for any finding of liability." The Court also declared unconstitutional the new Medicaid law's provision that allowed the State to join together in a single lawsuit hundreds or became etfective. occurred before July 1, 1994." 2 D e  J D a

Tong (R Subject: Effect of Tween-80 and Safflower Oil, the Vehicles for Dextromethorphan and Compound 111, on the Citric Acid Aerosol Induced Coughing in the Guinea Pig. The accompanying table presents additional experimental data which may be relevant to my report of June 17, 1971, en- titled "Antitussive Activity of Compound 111 in the Conscious Guinea Pig". The coughing experiments were carried out as described in the June 17, 1971 report. Essentially, where the drugs, Compound 111, and dextromethorphan were used before, Data in the attached table indicate that these two drug vehicles did not enhance nor attenuate the cough responses. Thus, as far as the data can indicate, safflower oil did not counteract any possible antitussive effect of Compound 111, nor did Tween-80 provide any additive effect to dextromethorphan. their respective vehicles were used here. Wall FROM: RE: Document Disposal Suspension Notice Litigation has been filed which requires us to retain certain records, many, if not all, of which are already subject to Disposal Suspension under the Philip Morris Records Management Program. Please make sure that disposal of all records, regardless of the media, relating to the manufacturing, testing and composition of tobacco, tobacco products, paper, filter or any other material contained in, relating to or used in the manufacture, testing and composition of tobacco products is suspended. These records should be maintained in the forms and media in which they were originally created. This notice also continues the suspension of the recycling of computer, voicemail, or other electronic backup tapes which may contain records subject to this notice or subject to prior suspension notices, including the Appendix to the Records Management Manual titled Topics Subject to Disposal Suspension. If there is any question about whether a record is subject to this or any other suspension notices, the record should be retained, pending consideration of your legal department. Within the next ten days a comprehensive notice will be sent replacing prior Document Disposal Suspension Notices. That notice will set forth all records which must be retained because of the litigation. The notice will also address ways in which the financial burdens of retaining all forms of a I electronic and computer records can be alleviated. Colk 2

PITTSBURGH CHAPTER AMERI CAN STATISTICAL ASSOCIATION ANNUAL DINNER MEETING Time and Place: Tuesday,- April 15, 1975 Park Schenley Speaker: Dr. Marvin A. Kastenbaum Director of Statistics .The Tobacco Institute Title: Epidemic by the Numbers Dr. Marvin A. Kastenbaum is currently the director of statistics at the Tobacco Institute in Washington, D.C. Prior to. assuming this position he was with the department of statistics at Stanford. He has also been on the faculty of the University of Wisconsin and has worked for Oak Ridge National Laboratory, the Institute of Human Biology at the University of Michigan, and the Atomic Bomb Casualty Commission. He is a fellow of ASA, the Royal Statistical Society, and American Association for the Advancement of Science. Abstract overuse of the term "epidemic" by well-meaning public officials and members of the scientific establishment may ultimately yield a diminishing response from the citizenry at whom. it is directed. How often can "Epidemic" be proclaimed throughout the land before the inhabitants thereof react as if The Boy were crying, "Wolf," again?
SRASS

FROM: The Tobacco Institute, Inc., 2735 K Street, N.W., Washington, D.C. 20006 Contact: William Kloeprer, Jr. FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE Smoking Is Probably Not Associated With Heart Dis sease, Swedish Scientists Find; Heredity Implicated Washington - Both the tendency to smoke, and susceptibility to respiratory symptams and heart disease, may be due to inherited constitutional differences between people, according to a series of Swedish studies reportea in Tobacco and Health Research. The publication digests scientific papers on subjects related to tobacco use and health, from medical and technical journals throughout the world. It is published by the Tobacco Institute. Two of the Swedish investigators, it notes, concluded that cigarette smoking is probably not associated with coronary heart disease, high blood pressure or high blood cholesterol levels. TEHR also reports that lung cancer of all types has been found to be three to four times more common in the Occidental European-American) immigrant population of Israel than in the Oriental (Asian-African) immigrants, even though smoking is about the same in both groups. And an international survey of eight major metropolitan areas, an English study found, turned up data called by the author incomprenensible according to current ideas as to how smoking affects lung cancer incidence." Genetics and the Heart The two Swedish studies involved twins. Twins are widely used in € P examinations of the possible effects of heredity upon disease, since the inherit tance lactors operating in each pair can be determined precisely. One (more)

Meyers (213) 641-2051 #S-32 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE James Snapp, insurance broker and former Mayor of El Cajon, today urged his friends and neighbors to support Californians for Common Sense in the organization's fight against the smoking prohibitions proposition, Proposition 5, on the November ballot. "The burden on California taxpayers has reached the limit," Snapp said. "The people, through Proposition 13, said they don't want this kind of spending. "Now comes the smoking prohibitions proposition that will be on our November ballot. It would cost an additional $43 million in local and state tax money to pay for an enormous system of expensive signs (at every entrance to every facility of every state and local governmental entity), law enforcement and court costs. "This additional tax load is not necessary. I am supporting Californians for Common Sense to defeat this needless and costly initiative." Co-chairmen of Californians for Common Sense, the organization campaigning for defeat of Proposition 5, are Houston I. Flournoy, dean of the University of Southern California Center for Public Affairs, Katherine B. Dunlap, prominent conservationist and civic $ leader and John F. Henning, executive secretary-treasurer of the - : California Labor Federation (AFL-CIO). # # #

MICHAEL A. MILES REMARKS ECONOMIC CLUB OF CHICAGO Tuesday, February 9, 1993 Thank you and thank you ladies and gentlemen. It's a pleasure to be here. When I was invited to speak to you, la asked ira what you might like to hear me talk about. He said that I could talk about anything I wanted to, as long as Isaid something reallyinteresting. This reminded me of an occasion back in the 1960's, when the comedian Mort Sahl was introduced by a master of ceremonies who said, "Come on out, This kind of introduction is, of course, a comedian's kiss of death, but Sahl, who was both ultra-liberal and irreverently anti-establishment, was up to the occasion. He came out, looked at the MC, looked at the audience, and said Mort, and say something really funny." "John Foster Duiles." This brought down the house. Well, I've been called on to say something really interesting, and while it's probably not house-bnnging-down matenial, I hope some of it will be interesting to you. There are two subjects I'd like to touch on this evening. First, because I've discovered that Philip Morris' size and mix of businesses make it the object of considerable public interest, l'd like to give you a brief overview of the company, and the strategies by which we are managing it. Second, I'd like to take a few minutes to talk about what I will call "science fiction," the problems that this science fiction creates for businesses in general and our business in particular, and some thoughts about what can be done to solve, or at least lessen, these problems. Tol begin with, then, let me tell you a little about Philip Morris. In its combined operations, Philip Morris is probably the world's largest consumer packaged goods company. In its component parts, PM is also the worid's largest international cigarette company, the second largest food company Last year, revenues for our worldwide operations totaled a little more than 59 billion dollars, which we expect will again put us in the top ten on Fortune's list of the largest industrial companies when that list is published in We have 166,000 employees working in 1,100 facilities in 160 countries around the worid. Frye Philip Morris Incorporated 4001 Commerce Road Richmond, Virginia 23261 (703) 275-8361 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE STAFF AT PHILIP MORRIS RESEARCH CENTER CONSISTS OF LEADING SCIENTISTS IN MANY FIELDS RESEARCH CENTER TOWER OFFERS RESEARCH FLEXIBILITY AND AN ATMOSPHERE OF SCIENTIFIC FREEDOM At Philip Morris's Research Center in Richmond, Va. tobacco and its various smoke compounds undergo every type of analysis under the survelllance of a professional staff of 190, including 40 Ph.D.'s. Total personnel at the Research Center is expected to be about 400 when the new Research Center Tower is completed in late 1972. Every relevant scientific discipline is represented by one or more persons on the research staff, and sometimes by entire teams of specialists. Fields of investigation include all ap- propriate branches of chemical and physical analysis, including smoke chemistry, chromatography, spectrophotometry, cigarette technology, biochemistry, agronomy, microbiology, psychology, 2 - filter development, flavor formulation, psychodynamics of smoking, organic chemistry, isolation and identification of volatile flavoring 5 constituents, and many others. PROJECT NAME: CO REMOVAL USING INORGANIC SALTS BUDGET: $16,639 PROJECT DESCRIPTION: : Principle Project Objectives The principle objective of this study is to evaluate carbon monoxide removal from cigarette smoke using ash or components of ash. The carbon monoxide removal from smoke using ashes, such as coal, paper, wood and tobacco will be optimized. The minerals in the ashes will be determined to elucidate the mechanism responsible for the carbon monoxide removal. The effect of ash addition on cigarette taste and tar and nicotine levels will be evaluated. A procedure for ash addition which is effective, condusive to mass production of cigarettes and acceptable to consumers, will be examined. YEAR 80 MONTH JL ML ML s X 16 12 8 4 D PROJECT COMPONENTS Literature Survey Preparation of Cigarettes CO Analysis Ash Analysis Tar, Nicotine Analysis Report A a 39 Hrs. to Date - 425 Total Hrs. Budgeted == 9% CO removals ranging from 15 to 40 8 have been observed when cigarette ash, coal ash and wood ash were added to cigarette tobacco. Coal, wood, paper and cigarette ash was analyzed using X-ray defraction and electron microprobe. Caco3, a component of the wood and cigarette ash was added to tobacco and some CO removal was observed. Attempts have been made to add ash via the RL but with little success. A study of the effect of moisture on the CO removal of ash has been investigated. M. Skladanowski PREPARED BY Hgnsnenyer

AMMONIA DETERMINATION When cigarette smoke is drawn through a Cambridge filter very little ammonia or ammonium salts are detected. Possibly the ammonia in the first puff comes through the filter. After the first puff the increasing deposit of acids on the filter combines with the ammonia and removes it from the gas strcam. When no Cambridge filter is used, 95% free ammonia and ammonium salts are collected in 80 ml of .018 N H2s04. Since the concentration of ammonia in cigarette smoke is quite low compared to the amount of acetic, formie and other acids present, we do not feel that the 40-70 ug./cig. represents free ammonia. Procedure - Two charcoal filter cigarettes are smoked for each determination. The smoke is dispersed through 80 ml of .018 N H2S04 in a specially designed trap by means of a coarse fritted disc. The solution is added to a 100 ml volumetric flask containing about 1.5 gm. of permutit. The permutit has been screened and washed 3 times with 25 ml portions of water. The flask is shaken for 15 minutes on a Burrel wrist action shaker. If the desired agitation is not achieved, the flask is shaken by hand. The acid solution is poured off and the permutit is washed 3 times with 25 ml portions of distilled water. Five ml of water and 1 ml of 10% NaoH is added to the permutit. The flask is shaken again for 5 minutes. The addition of 60-70 ml water 1s followed by 3 ml Nesslers reagent. The flask is filled to the mark with water, inverted many times for mixing, and allowed to stand 30 I minutes. 00073440 Blank - The blank is processed in the same manner as the sample; except, of course, the .018 N H2S04 solution contains no dissolved smoke.

Lanzillotti Date: February 17, 1982 Weekly Meeting with New Products Development Objectives: Smoke and evaluate samples prepared during the week preceeding Conclusions: Two sets of samples containing chocolate filler were smoked. One set contained a mixed fruit flavor in the tube walls, and the other set had an apple flavor with high boiling point tobacco flavors in the tube Both sets of samples were attached to 2.5/ 48 C.A. filters diluted by about The concentration of the fruit flavors which were included in the extrusion mixture for each sample were felt to be too high. The fruity notes were described as being overpowering. It was felt by some that the dilution was too great and had reduced the volume of smoke delivery too much. Five additional sets of samples were smoked. These samples had no filler inside of the tubes. Flavorants were added to the tube wall mixtures prior to extrusion for each set. The reactions to each were as follows: Anise flavor - Strong pack aroma, no detectable sidestream contribution, Fire-cured tobacco flavor - Chocolate-cooked tobacco-like pack aroma, no detectable sidestream contribution, no detectable flavor contribution. Oriental tobacco flayor - Green pack aroma, sharp green sidestream aroma, Black cigar tobacco flavor - No contribution to pack aroma, no detectable sidestream contribution, woody, cellulosic chemical flavor. Burley tobacco flavor - Fermented mowed weeds aroma, tobacco-like sidestream not objectionable. Flavor similar to aroma of rotten weeds. Chris Kounnas pointed out that since these samples had no filler and produced little smoke, the concentration of flavors delivered was probably too great for the quantity of smoke delivered. It was therefore difficult to evaluate the compatibility of these flavorants with extruded tobacco smoke. (Recrired in rerised, form 17 dagust 1984) Abstract- Evidence of noncomparability of sell-formed smoker and nonsmoker groups of adolescents from the Child Health and Development Studies of the University of California. Berkeley. was found in a study of antecedent psychosocial characteristics (observed at age 10) before the adoption of the smoking habit. With possible confounding factors controlled, eventual smokers showed significantly greater prevalence than nonsmokers of Type A personality traits. extraversion. psychoticism. anger. andi restless sleep. Eventual smokers were lower in socio- cconomic status than nonsmokers. and also exhibited signihcantly lower mean scores fon the Raven Progressive Matrices and Peabody Picture Vocabulary tests. For each trait. the. trends of the data were consistent in boys and girls Since many of these traits are shown to "track" into adult life. where they are then related to coronary heart disease. the role of self-sclection requires further consideration in causal inferences about smoking and coronary heart discuse. INTRODUCTION INIR RECENT years. many published studies have shown an association that suggests a role for psychosocial factors in the pathogenesis of CHD [1. 2]. In the Framingham Study. univariate and multivariate analyses showed a positive relationship of certain psycho- social factors to CHD and also to cigurette smoking [3-5]. The pervasive question. of temporal precedence and u priori sell-sclection still requires further clarification. however. In the absence of controlled experiments. the ellects of cigarette smoking on health have been inferred from observational studies that compare persons who smoke: with nonsmokers. In these comparisons. the disease outcomes are assumed to occur in cohorts ofsmokers and nonsmokers who were initially similar in all relevant characteristics except for the difference in smoking habit. Very little evidence has been available, however. to The unique data of the Child Health and Development Studies (CHDS) of the University of Califomia, Berkeley. provide an opportunity to check this assumption by examining antecedent characteristics associated with teenage smoking [6-8]. VIRGINIA PA49g" NEWS RELEASE BULLETIN: NEVADA May 15, 1999 Nevada Attorney General Frankie Sue Del Papa issued a letter to about 60 cigarette wholesalers in the state. The letter warned that those wholesalers who do not set up escrow accounts, into which they are required to pay $1.88 per carton for potential judgements stemming from the sale of cigarettes made by uon-signatories or gray-market cigarettes, will face significant fines. The fines are up to three times the amount the wholesalers are required to pay into the escrow accounts. Also, the Attorney General stated that a wholesaler may be banned from selling cigarettes within the state of Nevada if be commits more than one violation. Vevada's "Model Statute Legislation" became effective on May 24, 1999. In the opinion of Carolina Tobacco Company, trademark owaer and sole importer of "ROGER" brand cigarettes, the Nevada state authoritles will have 00 choice but to go after tbe wholesalers/jobbers of gray-market cigarettes. There is no process within the Master Settlement Agreement to catitle state authorities to seek compensation from the signatories of the Master Settlement Agreement for the sale of cigarettes originally manufactured for export within their state. Carolina Tobacco Company is also of the opinion that Nevada state authorities, as well as other state authorities, will turn to wholesalers/jobbers of cigarettes manufactured by non-signatories. State authorities will be obligated to do sO under the terms of the Master Settlement Agreemeut, if they are unable to obtain compensation from the aon-signatory manufacturers themselves. 8 S 5 Liaison Office: 5533 S W. MACO M Institute for Environment IEHI and Health MRC Madical Resnarch Councll PRESS RELEASE Embargoed untll 11:00am Thursday 23rd May 1996 NEW REPORT ON HEALTH EFFECTS OF INDOOR AIR POLLUTION A major new report Into the health offocts of some key indoor air pollutants in the home, pub- lished today (23/5/96), suggests that house dust mites and nitrogen dioxide (from gas cook- ers) are likely to be the greatest source of airborne health problems in the home. The report, EHAssessment on Indoor. Air Quality in the Home, was produced for the Departmient of the Environment by the Medical Research Council's institute for Environment and Health In Leicester. It looks at five types of pollutants in the home - nitrogen dioxide (NO2), formaldehyde, volatile organic compounds (including benzene and common solvents), house dust mitos and fungi and bacteria. Using data trom the Building Research Establishment, also released in a report today, it evaluates the potential adverse health effects of these poliutants and puts the findings In a national and international perspectivo. The report recognises that the risks to health from dust mites and nitrogen dioxide are not known, but nonetheless recommends a reduction in oxposure. Whilst the other pollutants studied may be hazardous, the report concludes that there is no evidence that current levels in UK homes pose a risk to health. But, as a general principle, it recommends reducing the HEOINE levels of indoor pollutants as a prudent measure. As well as taking an overview of current knowledge, the report Identifies a number of Impor- tant areas for future research. These include studies to: evaluate the potontial health bonetits - from reducing levels of dust mites; establish clearly whether or not high NO2 leveis cause U more... P

Rathke 416-964-8300 or Laura Gongos 412/471-9600 RATHKE NAMED CEO BURSON-MARSTELLERICANADA PITTSBURGH OFFICE ANNOUNCES NEW GENERAL MANAGER PITTSBURGH, Nov. 9 - Sheila Wells Rathke, a 17-year veteran of Burson-Marsteller and general manager of the Pittsburgh office for the past seven years, has been named Chief Executive Officer of Burson-Marsteller's Canadian operations. As part of Rathke's expanded responsibilities, she will be in charge of developing and servicing business and overseeing all operational aspects of Burson-Marsteller's offices in Toronto, Montreal, Ottawa and Vancouver, effective December 1. Laura Gongos, a senior vice president and 14-year veteran of Burson-Marsteller/ Pittsburgh, will succeed Rathke as general nanager of the Pittsburgh office. "These appointments represent logical transitions for two individuals who have made important contributions to Burson-Marsteller," said Don Cogman, President and Chief Executive Officer, Burson-Marsteller/Americas. 2071277124 Page 1 Note for Padoan, Art *** URGENT *** Sarmento, Roberto Thu, Mar 27, 1997 11:22. AM From: Date: Subject: EEMA To: Padoan, Art Mr. William H. Webb, Chief Operating Officer of Philip Morris Companies Inc., is pleased to announce the appointment of Mr. Jean- Claude Kunz, Vice President Central Europe, to the position of President EEMA Region, effective immediately. In his new role, Jean- Claude will report to Mr. Andreas Gembler, President of Philip Morris Jean-Claude began his career with Philip Morris EEMA in 1983 as Business Development Analyst. In 1984, he was promoted to General Manager Eastern Europe and in 1986, he was appointed General Manager for the Levant and parts of the Middle East. In 1990, he was appointed Area Director Eastern Europe and in 1992, Area Director Central Europe. In 1993, he was appointed to his current position of Vice President Central Europe. Jean-Claude has played a key role in the success of EEMA's acquisitions and the development of the emerging markets of Central Europe and the Balkans. With the transfer of the domestic Scandinavian and Finnish markets to Scandinavia / Finland / Baltics / Duty Free will assume responsibility for Central Europe and is appointed Vice President Switzerland, Central PHans Fluri, Vice President Eastern Europe, will assume additional responsibility for the Baltics and is appointed Vice President Eastern International Inc. the EU: PC Georges Diserens, Vice President Switzerland, Europe and Duty Free. Europe and the Baltics. Also reporting to Jean-Claude will be: P Rudi Schweizer, Senior Vice President P John Guarino, Director Africa and Levant P Jacques Guyot, Vice President Operations P Kathleen Linehan, Vice President Corporate Affairs P Turhan Talu, Vice President GCC. and Turkey P Jean-Michel Toinet, Vice President Marketing Please join us in congratulating Jean-Claude and in wishing him every success in his new position as President EEMA Region. At the same time, join us in extending our best wishes to Georges and Hans in their new responsibilitics.

Sample Letter Concerned Citizen April 1998 The Honorable Office Address Washington, D.C. Dear Senator or Representative United States Senate/or/United States House ofl Representatives Ia am writing to express my: strong opposition to S. 1415, Senator John McCain's tobacco legislation. As a concerned citizen, I am offended by many aspects of this legislation, including unfair taxes, the creation of a black market and sweeping FDA authority. The McCain bill constitutes modem day Prohibition. The FDA would have discretion under the McCain legislation to ban tobacco products immediately - without any Congressional action. The FDA is an unelected federal agency that should not be given unfettered authority to ban tobacco. Tobacco prohibition would foster an immediate black market and smuggling operations -creating a boon for organized crime. A ban on tobacco products also would be a crippling blow on many communities whose economic stability depends on the tobacco industry. Hundreds of thousands of people have jobs linked to the production, distribution and retailing oftobacco products. High cigarette taxes will cause job losses in every sector of the tobacco industry - from the seedbed to the sales counter. I am a hard-working taxpayer, and I support legislation that keeps tobacco products out of the hands ofminors. However, I strongly oppose any bill that infringes on an adult's right to smoke a legal product. Adults make up 98 percent of all smokers in the United States, and they will bear the burden of the huge tax increases proposed by Senator McCain. Iencourage you to vote against the McCain bill and any legislation that mirrors the devastating effects of the McCain bill. Thank you for your attention to this matter. 9 - o Respectfully,

June 13, 1988 To: From: A. L. Barnett J. J. Gohn Subject: Video Cassette Promotion Concepts The purpose of this memo is to forward a perspective on the potential tie-in of RJRT and MGM/UA for the purpose of leveraging this union with impactful consumer promotions utilizing pre-recorded video cassettes. In December 1987, focus groups were held in Atlanta to determine how CAMEL and Marlboro smokers would react to promotions which include pre-recorded video cassette films from Paramount Studios. This tie-in with Paramount was identical in concept to the proposed tie-in with The findings of these focus groups, although qualitative, in a single market, from a small sample, etc., illustrated a major lack of interest in buying video movies even at a discount price when they can be rented Background MGM/UA. - so cheaply and sO conveniently. e Perspective According to 1987 Simmons data, a high percentage of adult smokers own a VCR (38.7), however, only 18% of these VCR owners have ever bought a pre-recorded video cassette. An extremely large majority (97%) rent movies because: Rentals are cheap. Current movies can be rented for $2 or $3 and if they want to retain it, they can just record it on a blank tape. Hit titles are readily available. Most only watch a movie once. Rentals are extremely accessible. Most are rented where cigarettes are not sold but are becoming more available in supermarkets, drug stores and convenience stores. a : 8

Introduction: In my memorandum of 21 May, 1963, "Possible sources of nicotine", I compared the merits of obtaining nicotine from a specialty crop of N. rustica as against producing it from stalks left in the field. The conclusion was that if nicotine were to be produced it should be produced from a crop grown for that purpose. Recently, I came across a publication which explores this very question in some On the basis of the results presented it becomes possible to formulate a detail and confirms our preliminary conclusions. pilot program which is presented below for your consideration. 2. - Summary of Prior Field Trials: The experiences of the U.S.D.A., covering the period 1929-1938, in Browing tobacco as a source of nicotine are collected in U.S.D.A. Technical Bulletin No. 820, June 1942. This publication is available in the A.T.C. library under catalog No. T-7445 hence only the pertinent highlights will be reiterated here. a. Available nicotine from commercial types of tobacco, if entire leaf crop b. N. rustica, var. Brasilia, consistently yiclded 150 lbs. or more per acre when grown on fertile, moist soils. The whole plant of N. rustica can be used for extraction whereas stalks of commercial tobaccos, owing to their high degree of lignification, are not easily disrupted for extraction. c. The comparative tests were conducted in field plots widely scattered around the country, including plots in Virginia (Bowling Green and Arlington), Pennsylvania, Wisconain, Missouri, Oregon, California, North Carolina, Tennessee and a few others. As a result a wide variety of soils and climatic conditions d. When grown on typical soils of the dark-fired area, or in extreme southern regions, N. rustica did not outyield standard commercial varieties. Contractor will perform in a professional manner throughout the term of the Agreement. 2. Payment Int full and complete consideration for the services rendered by Contractor pursuant tol Paragraphs 1(a)-(d), PM1 USA will pay Contractor an amount not to exceed $4,241 upon PM USA's receipt of a detailed invoice and final reconciliation following complete performance of the agreement to the. reasonable satisfaction of PM USA. Total payment to Contractor PM USA for services rendered will not exceed I by $4,241.00.
