July 9, 1998 ABSTRACT A series of four independent, two-stage SENCAR: mouse skin painting bioassays were conducted with cigarette smoke condensates to examine the tumor promotion potential of 150 flavoring ingredients commonly used in the manufacture of American-style blended cigarettes. Groups consisting of 30 to 50 female SENCAR mice each were used; animals were treated once dermally with 50 ug 0f7,12-dimethylbenza/-anthracene as a tumor initiator. One week later, and thrice weekly for the next 26 weeks, mice received either 10 or 20 mg of smoke condensate from Test cigarettes containing mixtures of cigarette tobacco flavoring ingredients. For comparison, separate groups of mice were treated concurrently with smoke condensates prepared from Reference cigarettes having similar construction and tobacco blend, but without added flavoring ingredients. Negative and positive controls were treated with either acetone or 12-0- etradecanoyl-phorbol-13-acetate as promoters, respectively. Virtually all mice treated with the positive control material developed tumors and died prior to the scheduled study termination points. Background tumor formation and mortality were very low in all negative control groups. Survival rates and terminal body weights of mice treated with condensate samples from Test cigarettes were not significantly different from mice treated with condensates from Reference cigarettes. Similarly, the incidence of animals with actual tumors (grossly observable tumors at study termination), incidence of animals with cumulative tumor (maintained count of all tumors present for three consecutive weeks during hestudy), latency of cumulative tumors and tumor multiplicity in mice exposed to condensates from Test cigarettes with flavoring ingredients were not different from,values obtained with mice treated with Reference cigarette condensate. The results indicate that the addition of the flavoring ingredients to cigarette tobacco had no discernible effect on common indices oft tumorigenic response normally associated with mouse skin painting bioassays using non-flavored cigarette smoke condensates. omy sTatbmint Yluee Toe A bom  a 2

Karger. 1991. pp 105-114 Isolation of a Xenobiotic Metabolizing Cytochrome P-450 (P-450soK) with No Aromatase Activity from Placental Microsomes of Both Cigarette-Smoking and Yoshio Osawa. Tadavoshi Higashiyama. Kenji Shimizu'. Endocrine Biochemistry Depanment, Medical Foundation of Bufialo Rescarch nsttute. Buffalo. N.Y.. USA Placental Proteins Nonsmoking Mothers Nobutaka Yoshida' COPY FILE The presence of different monooxygenase activities has been docu- mented in human placental microsomes. The predominating cytochrome P- 450, that of androgen aromatase, catalyzes the biosynthesis of estrogens [1). Aromatase P-450 has been the object of numerous studies to determine its mechanism of action and to purify it (2, 3). Gough et al. 14) reported the prcscnce of another enzyme system which catalyzes the hydroxylation of xenobiotic substances. It has also been reported that a placental cytochrome P-450 is responsible for the hydroxylation of benzola)pyrene via aryl hydro- carbon hydroxylase (5-7). The low content of the responding cytochrome P- 450 in human placenta and instability during purification have made it difficult to isolate any other active P-450 enzyme. As a side beneft gained from our procedure to purify and characterize catalytically active aromatase P-450 (3), we found a fraction from the immunoafinity chromatography which showed a high level of xenobiotic activity with little contaminating aromatase activity. Through the use ofconventional purification procedures, we obtained a xenobiotically active P-450 with no aromatase activity. Previous studies on aryl hydrocarbon bydroxylase activity have demon- strated higher levels of this activity in smokers but not in nonsmokers (8, 9). SALONEN,t PIRJO POYHIA,t KAJ KOSKELA,t AND "National Public Health Institute, Department of Epidemiology, Mannerheimintie 166, 00280 Helsinki 28, Finland, tUniversity of Kuopio, Research Institute of Public Health, PL 40, 70101 Kuopio 10, Finland. and +Harvard School of Public Health, Department A school and community based intervention to influence health behavior and cardiovas- cular disease (CVD) risk factors in 13- to 15-year-old children was carried out in North Karelia, Finland. The intervention was carried out on two leveis: (a) an intensive interven- tion (II) in two schools and (b) a county-wide intervention (CI) in the rest of North Karelia, For the evaluation three matched pairs of schools were chosen: the two schools of the II, two schools to represent the CI and two schools from a reference county (R). 851 children, their parents, and their teachers were studied at the outset in 1978: and after the intervention in 1980. During the program the proportion of boys reporting to smoke atl least 1-21 times per month increased 12.6% in II, 8.2% in CI and 29.7% in the R schools (P < 0.001 between II and R) and in giris 9.0%, 18.0% and 20.0%, respectively. (P < 0.05 between II and R). The mean serum total cholesterol was 5.1 mmol/liter in 1978 and it decreased among boys 0.5 mmolliter: in all three school groups. Among girls. the decrease was 0.43 mmolliter (II), 0.35 mmolliter (CI), and 0.21 mmol/liter (R) (P < 0.01 between. II and R). The mean: amount of fat from milk and butter changed among boys -8 g (II), Og (CI), and +3 g (R) and among girls -168. -2g, and -Sg,respectively (both P: < 0.011 between. II and R). Thei intervention had no effect on blood pressure although there was some reported reduction in the salt consump- tion in the intervention schools. A relative decrease according to the intervention level was ob- served: among North Karelian children in occurrence of psychosomatic symptoms. The effects were not related to increases in bealth knowledge or changes in attitudes and did not lead, on Cardiovascular diseases (CVD) are the major, singular public health problem in most of the industrial worid, but especially in Finland (6, 11). A number of pro- spective studies have indicated that possibilities for CVD prevention lie in reduc- tion of well established risk factors: smoking, elevated serum cholesterol, and hypertension (6, 18, 22). Several preventive trials among adults are under way to test the hypothesis that risk factor reduction in the population will lead to: reduced mortality and morbidity from CVD (17, 25, 29). CHILIP MORRIS USA INTER-OFFICE CORRESPONDENCE 120 PARK AVENUE, NEWYORK, NY 10017-5592 DATE: May 13, 1991 TO: FROM: Distribution Marketing Information & Analysis/Ellen Fitzgerald SUBJECT: FULL MARGIN COMPETITIVE COUPON ACTIVITY Attached is the latest competitive supermarket coupon information through March 24, 1991) as reported by various data sources. Note: Media-delivered couponing information as reported by the Advertising Checking Bureau is currently available through February. SUMMARY RJR reduced the overall level of coupon support behind their Full Margin brands. This shift was driven by reductions in on-carton/in-store couponing. Philip Morris' Full Margin couponing increased versus a year-ago due to the various Fourth Quarter 1990 Direct Mail programs for Marlboro, Merit and Benson & Hedges. Lorillard significantly increased coupon support behind Newport, Kent and True. Importantly, this higher value coupon activity has had a positive impact on the brands' share pertormance in the supermarket trade class (as reported by the InfoScan Rapid Fact data base). In addition, Lorillard is using a new coupon delivery system: Register Receipt Coupons which delivers $5.00 coupons for Newport to American and Brown & Williamson are focusing their couponing efforts behind their Price Value/Sub-Generic brands and have consequently reduced support for the consumers at retail. manufacturers' Full Margin businesses. HIGHLIGHTS supermarket Full Margin couponing trends continue to be driven primarily by R.J. Reynolds (40% of volume sold on coupon) and Lorillard's recent emphasis behind their Full Margin brands (37% of volume) for the four-week period ending March 24th. However, note that RJR'S Full Margin couponing has lost momentum during First Quarter 1991. Full Margin's percent volume sold on coupon for the manufacturer is down from a high of 51% at the end of 1990 to its current level of 40%. Price Value couponing for R.J. Reynolds remained stable at around 62% Couponing for RJR's Full Margin brands declined primarily as a result of decreasing in-store/on-carton coupon activity. For the most current four-week period, the percent of stores with on-carton couponing for Winston decreased -24 points to 14% versus the prior period; Salem, -27 points to 16%; Camel, -27 points to 17%; and Vantage, With the exception of Camel, however, Full Margin coupon activity supported by media-delivered programs) for Winston (42% of volume sold on coupon), Salem (45%) and Vantage (57%) remained high relative to the industry average. Camel experienced a significant decline in volume sold on coupon (-16 points to only 19%) 6 due in part to reductions after the introductory support behind Ultra Lights. Additionally, it is likely that RJR is reducing the level of in-store/on-carton couponing % behind the brand to refocus support to Camel on pack sales in Convenience Outlets. during First Quarter 1991. -24 points to 18%.
